Bank Internasional, Medco, Tunas Baru: Indonesia Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-08-08T02:03:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/bank-internasional-medco-tunas-baru-indonesia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in Indonesian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the previous close.  The  Jakarta Composite index (JCI)  dropped 4.9 percent to 3,921.64.  Energy companies: Crude oil futures declined as much as 3.7
percent to $83.68 a barrel in after-hours trading in  New York .  PT Medco Energi Internasional (MEDC IJ), Indonesia’s
biggest listed oil company, dropped 5.1 percent to 2,350 rupiah
and PT Energi Mega Persada (ENRG IJ), the second largest, sank
13 percent to 210 rupiah.  Metal producers: Nickel for three-month delivery plunged
4.8 percent to $22,505 a metric ton in London Aug. 5, the most
since May 23. Tin fell 4.5 percent to $23,250 a ton in after-
hours trading today, extending a 4.5 percent decline on Aug. 5.
PT International Nickel Indonesia (INCO IJ), the nation’s
largest producer of the metal, dropped 6.1 percent to 3,825
rupiah and PT Timah (TINS IJ), the largest tin producer, tumbled
11 percent to 2,100 rupiah.  PT Bank CIMB Niaga (BNGA IJ): The company’s first-half net
income rose to 1.55 trillion rupiah ($181 million) from 1.13
trillion rupiah a year earlier, while net interest income gained
to 3.80 trillion rupiah from 3.53 trillion rupiah, the bank said
in a statement published in Bisnis  Indonesia . Bank CIMB Niaga
fell 7.9 percent to 1,520 rupiah.  PT Bank Internasional Indonesia (BNII IJ): The unit of
 Malaysia ’s biggest lender by assets, Malayan Banking Bhd. plans
to raise 500 billion rupiah through a subordinated-debt offering
in the fourth quarter, Bisnis Indonesia reported, citing
unidentified people from Indonesia’s central bank. Stephen Liestyo, a director at Bank Internasional, confirmed the lender
will sell bonds soon, the report said. The stock retreated 7.4
percent to 500 rupiah.  PT Perusahaan Gas Negara (PGAS IJ): Indonesia biggest
distributor of the fuel plans to build a floating liquefied-
natural-gas terminal in Banten or Lampung to supply PT Krakatau
Steel and other customers in western Java, Technology and
Development Director Jobi Triananda said. Gas Negara fell 12
percent to 3,175 rupiah.  PT Tunas Baru Lampung (TBLA IJ): The company’s net income
may rise to 600 billion rupiah this year from 246.7 billion a
year earlier,  Bisnis Indonesia  reported, citing Corporate
Secretary Hardy Phan. The palm oil producer expects revenue to
increase to 4 trillion rupiah from 2.95 trillion rupiah, the
report said. Tunas Baru tumbled 11 percent to 660 rupiah.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
